Macedonians hold a referendum to decide whether to change the name of the country
Last Sunday, the Macedonian people held a referendum on renaming the "Republic of North Macedonia", a move that would resolve a decades-long dispute with Greece that had blocked Macedonia's applications for membership in the European Union and NATO.
Greece, which has a province called Macedonia, maintains that the name of its northern neighbor constitutes a claim to its territory and has vetoed its entry into NATO and the EU.
In June, the two governments reached an agreement on the proposed new name, but nationalist opponents argue that the change would undermine the ethnic identity of Macedonia's majority Slavic population.
President Gjorge Ivanov has stated that he will not participate in the referendum, and a boycott campaign casts doubt on whether the minimum required participation of 50% will be reached for the referendum to be valid.
The question indicated in the referendum paper is: "Are you in favour of joining NATO and the EU, with the acceptance of the agreement with Greece?".
Supporters of the name change, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, argue that it is a price worth paying to achieve Macedonia's accession, one of the countries that was created following the disintegration of Yugoslavia, to bodies such as the EU and NATO.
“Today I have come to vote for the future of the country, so that the young people of Macedonia can live freely in the European Union, because it means that all of us will have a safer life,” said 79-year-old Olivera Georgijevska in Skopje.
Although it is not legally binding, a sufficient number of parliamentarians have stated that they will follow the result of the vote to make it decisive.
To change the name, a two-thirds majority is required in Parliament.
The State Electoral Commission reported that no irregularities had occurred at 1 p.m.
However, the turnout was only 16%, compared to 34% registered in the last parliamentary elections, held in 2016, in which 66% of registered people voted.
“I have come to vote for my children, our place is in Europe,” 62-year-old Gjose Tanevski said in Skopje.
Macedonian Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica and his son Dushko voted in a referendum held in Macedonia on the country's name change, which would open the way for him to join the European Union and NATO in Strumica, Macedonia, on September 30, 2018.
In front of the Parliament of Skopje, Vladimir Kavardarkov, 54, was preparing a small stage and placing chairs in front of the tents installed by the people who would boycott the referendum.
“We are in favor of NATO and the EU, but we want to stick to it with our heads held high, not through the back door,” Kavadarkov said.
“We are a poor country, but we have dignity.
If they do not want to accept us as Macedonia, we can turn to other countries, such as China and Russia, and be part of the Eurasian integration.”
Prime Minister Zaev says NATO membership will be accompanied by more than necessary investments in Macedonia, which has a unemployment rate of more than 20%.
“I believe that the vast majority will vote in favour, because more than 80% of the citizens are in favour of the EU and NATO,” Zaev said.
Zaev said a “yes” would mean “confirmation of our future.”
In a poll published on Monday by the Macedonian Political Research Institute, between 30% and 43% of voters would participate in the referendum, a figure below the minimum required participation.
According to the results of another poll, conducted by the Macedonian network Telma TV, 57% of respondents plan to vote on Sunday.
Of these, 70% said they would vote “yes”.
For the referendum to be valid, the turnout must be 50% plus one vote.
A failure in the referendum would be the first hard time for the policy of the pro-Western government since it took over in May last year.
