John Edward: Language skills are essential for global citizens
Independent schools in Scotland maintain a track record of academic excellence that has continued in 2018 with another series of excellent exam results, which is reinforced with individual and collective success in sports, art, music and other community efforts.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS) strive to offer a service of the best level to students and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare students for further and higher studies, for the career they choose and for their place as citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a personalized school curriculum, we note that modern languages remain a very popular and desired subject of choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, you will get to his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, you will reach his heart.”
This is a very important reminder that we cannot depend only on English if we want to establish relationships and build trust with people from other countries.
Based on the recent results of this year’s exams, we can see that languages lead the classification tables with the highest qualifications in independent schools.
68% of the students who studied foreign languages obtained a higher grade A.
The data, collected from 74 SCIS member schools reflected that 72% of students obtained a higher A rating in Mandarin, while 72% of German students, 69% of French students, and 63% of Spanish students also obtained an A rating.
This shows that Scotland’s independent schools support foreign languages as vital skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Currently, languages, as a subject of choice, are maintained in the same consideration as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in curricula from independent schools and elsewhere.
A 2014 survey by the Employment and Skills Commission of the United Kingdom revealed that of the reasons that employers gave for the fact that it cost them to cover the vacancies, 17% were attributed to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly indispensable to prepare young people for their future careers.
As there are more and more potential job opportunities that require languages, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career that a person chooses, if he has learned a second language, he will have a real advantage in the future with a permanent competition like this.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically puts a multilingual person ahead of the competition.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK, 75% were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to hold a conversation, and French, with 15% of speakers, was the only language with a double-digit percentage.
For this reason, investing in language teaching is important for today’s children.
Knowing several languages, especially those of developed economies, will give children better opportunities to find important work.
In Scotland, there is diversity among schools in terms of the languages they teach.
Some schools focus more on more traditional modern languages, while others teach languages that are considered to be more important for the UK in the future, towards 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever the interest of your child, you can always choose from a number of languages in independent schools, which have teaching staff specialized in this field.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that will prepare children and equip them with the skills they need to succeed, no matter what the future holds.
In today’s global business environment, it cannot be denied that languages continue to have a vital importance for the future of the country, and this must be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should really be considered “international communication skills”.
Independent schools will continue to offer this option, diversity and excellence to young Scots.
It has to be done.
John Edward is Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
