Harvard Students Take a Course in Rest Habits
This year, a new course at Harvard University has allowed its students to sleep longer, in an attempt to combat the increasingly widespread culture of studying all night long, stimulated by caffeine.
One scholar observed that students at the world’s number-one university are often clued in to the basic aspects of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
She was inspired to create the course after giving a talk about the impact sleep deprivation had on learning.
“At the end of the talk, a girl came up to me and said, ‘Why are they telling me now, all this, in my last year?’
He said no one had ever told him about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, first implemented this year, explains to students the basic concepts of how good sleep habits improve academic and sports performance, as well as overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the University's health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after learning that some students suffered from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The course, which is one hour long, includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one section there is an image of a bedroom, where students have to click on coffee cups, curtains, bamboos and books to receive information about the effects of caffeine and light, about how sports performance affects sleep deprivation, and about the importance of maintaining a bedtime routine.
In another section, participants are informed about how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression, and cancer.
Next, a campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily route.
“We know that the behavior of the students will not change immediately.
But we believe they have the right to know, as one has the right to know the health effects of smoking cigarettes,” Professor Czeisler said.
The culture of pride of staying up all night still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and the growing pressure that students suffer make sleep deprivation an ever-increasing problem.
Making sure to enjoy a good quality sleep for long enough should be a “secret weapon” of students to combat stress, fatigue and anxiety, he added, even to avoid gaining weight, since sleep deprivation puts the brain in a mode of starvation and makes students always gain.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies Chemistry and Physical Biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after attending one of his classes in his final year during his first year at Harvard.
Raymond commented that the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to promote the course throughout the campus.
The next step, he expects, is to ask graduate students to undertake a similar program of study before joining the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students take into account the fact of setting an alarm when they go to sleep and when they wake up, and be aware of the harmful effects of “blue light” emitted by electronic screens and LED lights, which can alter the harmony of their circadian rhythm and cause problems.
