HIV/AIDS: China notifies an increase in new cases of 14%
China has announced a 14% increase in the number of people living with HIV and AIDS.
There are more than 820,000 people affected in the country, according to health officials.
In the second quarter of 2018 alone, 40,000 new cases were reported.
The vast majority of new cases are of sexual transmission, unlike what happened in the past.
Traditionally, HIV spread rapidly in some regions of China due to infected blood transfusions.
However, the number of people who contract HIV for this cause has been reduced to almost zero, according to statements from Chinese health officials at a conference in Yunnan province.
Year after year, however, the number of people living with HIV and AIDS in China has increased by 100,000.
Sexual transmission of HIV is a serious problem for China’s LGBT community.
Homosexuality was decriminalized in China in 1997, but discrimination against the LGBT community is common.
Taking into account the conservative values of the country, studies estimate that between 70 and 90% of men who maintain homosexual relationships will end up marrying a woman.
Many of the transmissions of diseases are due to the lack of adequate precautions for sexual relations.
Since 2003, the Chinese government has promised universal access to HIV medication as part of an effort to address the problem.
