The National Foundation spies on the secret life of bats
A new research carried out on a Scottish Highlands farm aims to find out how bats use the landscape to feed themselves.
It is expected that the findings could provide new data on the behavior of these unique flying mammals and help in future conservation activities.
The study by scientists from the National Foundation of Scotland will continue to be soprano and common bats, as well as northern eared bats and water bats in the Inverewe Botanical Garden, located in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in key locations of the property to keep track of the activities of the bats during the season.
Volunteers and staff from the UK’s National Health Service will also conduct mobile surveys with portable detectors.
The sound analysis of the recordings by experts will determine the sound frequency of the bats and what each species does.
With this information, a report and a habitat map will be created to create a detailed picture of the landscape of your behavior.
Rob Dewar, Natural Conservation Advisor at the National Foundation of Scotland, hopes the results will show which areas of habitat are most important for bats and how each species uses them.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as grassland creation, and how to improve forest maintenance for bats and other associated species.
The population of bats in Scotland and the rest of the United Kingdom has declined considerably in the last century.
Building construction and restoration tasks threaten bats, as they affect nests and can cause habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lighting also pose a risk, as do sledgehammers and chemical treatments used in building materials, as well as domestic cat attacks.
In fact, bats are not blind.
However, due to their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when they have to catch a prey.
They use a sophisticated echo localization technique to locate insects and obstacles that interfere with their flight.
The National Foundation of Scotland, responsible for taking care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes bats very seriously.
It has ten experts with the proper training, who carry out surveys, nest inspections and, sometimes, rescues on a regular basis.
The organisation has even created Scotland's first and only rattan reserve at the Threeve Estate, located in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland's ten rattan species.
The estate's administrator, David Thompson, claims it is the ideal territory for the species.
“Here at Threeave, we have a big area for bats,” he says.
“We have old buildings, lots of old trees and quite a good habitat.
But we still don’t know many aspects of bats, so the work we do here and other properties will help us better understand what they need to grow.”
It notes the importance of checking whether there are rattans before carrying out maintenance tasks on property, as it may be that the possible involuntary destruction of a single maternity nest kills more than 400 females and young, which could result in the disappearance of an entire local population.
The bats are protected and it is illegal to kill them, attack them, disturb them and destroy their nests.
Elisabeth Ferrell, an official at the Scottish Rat Conservation Foundation, has encouraged people to take a step forward to help.
He said: “We still have a lot to learn from bats and, in the case of some of our species, we don’t have enough data on their population.”
